│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs during peeling of the last iteration of a loop               │
│ (PeelLast=true) in peelLoop. Specifically, when adjusting users of the        │
│ original exit PHI values, the code calls replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E)).  │
│ If E (the incoming value along the latch into the exit PHI) is a constant or  │
│ otherwise not cloned, VMap.lookup(E) returns null, leading to an assertion    │
│ failure in Value::replaceAllUsesWith(<null>). The minimized test indicates    │
│ this situation arises after completely unrolling an inner loop, leaving an    │
│ LCSSA PHI in the outer loop's exit whose incoming value from the latch is a   │
│ constant.                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The inner loop is completely unrolled.                                      │
│ - Then the outer loop is peeled with PeelLast=true: "PEELING loop             │
│ %outer.header with iteration count 1!".                                       │
│ - The crash happens at peelLoop's replacement of exit values.                 │
│ - The first transformation point is Value::doRAUW triggered from              │
│ P->replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E)). This suggests VMap.lookup(E) returned  │
│ null.                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ When PeelLast is true, peelLoop records ExitValues mapping each exit PHI P to │
│ the value E incoming from the latch before peeling. After cloning one peeled  │
│ iteration, it tries to replace all uses of P with the cloned equivalent of E  │
│ via VMap.lookup(E). However, not all incoming values are cloned/mapped:       │
│ constants and other values outside the cloned loop are not inserted into      │
│ VMap, so VMap.lookup(E) returns nullptr. Attempting                           │
│ replaceAllUsesWith(nullptr) triggers the assertion. This matches the test     │
│ case name hinting at a constant LCSSA PHI value after unrolling the inner     │
│ loop.                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp                                │
│ - Location: Around the code that replaces exit PHI uses when PeelLast is      │
│ true.                                                                         │
│ - Change: Use the original value E if no mapping exists in VMap.              │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit:                                                                         │
│   for (const auto &[P, E] : ExitValues)                                       │
│ -     P->replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E));                                  │
│ +     {                                                                       │
│ +       // VMap does not contain entries for values that were not cloned      │
│ +       // (e.g., constants or values defined outside the loop). In that case │
│ +       // the correct replacement is the original value itself.              │
│ +       Value *NewV = VMap.lookup(E);                                         │
│ +       if (!NewV)                                                            │
│ +         NewV = E;                                                           │
│ +       P->replaceAllUsesWith(NewV);                                          │
│ +     }                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures constants and other unmapped values are handled safely and       │
│ correctly.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to replacing uses with a null pointer when the incoming exit │
│ value is not cloned (e.g., a constant). By falling back to the original value │
│ when no VMap entry exists, we avoid the assertion and preserve correct        │
│ semantics. This fix maintains correctness for both cloned and non-cloned      │
│ values and prevents the crash during last-iteration peeling.                  │
