  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs during peeling of
the last iteration of a loop (PeelLast=true) in peelLoop. Specifically, when
adjusting users of the original exit PHI values, the code calls
replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E)). If E (the incoming value along the latch into
the exit PHI) is a constant or otherwise not cloned, VMap.lookup(E) returns null,
leading to an assertion failure in Value::replaceAllUsesWith(<null>). The
minimized test indicates this situation arises after completely unrolling an
inner loop, leaving an LCSSA PHI in the outer loop's exit whose incoming value
from the latch is a constant.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The inner loop is
completely unrolled.\n- Then the outer loop is peeled with PeelLast=true:
\"PEELING loop %outer.header with iteration count 1!\".\n- The crash happens at
peelLoop's replacement of exit values.\n- The first transformation point is
Value::doRAUW triggered from P->replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E)). This suggests
VMap.lookup(E) returned null.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWhen PeelLast is true,
peelLoop records ExitValues mapping each exit PHI P to the value E incoming from
the latch before peeling. After cloning one peeled iteration, it tries to replace
all uses of P with the cloned equivalent of E via VMap.lookup(E). However, not
all incoming values are cloned/mapped: constants and other values outside the
cloned loop are not inserted into VMap, so VMap.lookup(E) returns nullptr.
Attempting replaceAllUsesWith(nullptr) triggers the assertion. This matches the
test case name hinting at a constant LCSSA PHI value after unrolling the inner
loop.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp\n- Location: Around the code that replaces
exit PHI uses when PeelLast is true.\n- Change: Use the original value E if no
mapping exists in VMap.\n\nEdit:\n  for (const auto &[P, E] : ExitValues)\n-
P->replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(E));\n+     {\n+       // VMap does not contain
entries for values that were not cloned\n+       // (e.g., constants or values
defined outside the loop). In that case\n+       // the correct replacement is
the original value itself.\n+       Value *NewV = VMap.lookup(E);\n+       if
(!NewV)\n+         NewV = E;\n+       P->replaceAllUsesWith(NewV);\n+
}\n\nThis ensures constants and other unmapped values are handled safely and
correctly.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to replacing uses with a null
pointer when the incoming exit value is not cloned (e.g., a constant). By falling
back to the original value when no VMap entry exists, we avoid the assertion and
preserve correct semantics. This fix maintains correctness for both cloned and
non-cloned values and prevents the crash during last-iteration peeling.",
